  "companies": [],
  "statement": "# Course Schedule\n\nReturn whether all courses can be completed given prerequisite pairs `[course, prerequisite]`.\n\n## Examples\n\n**Example 1**\n\n```text\nInput: numCourses = 2, prerequisites = [[1,0]]\nOutput: true\n```\n\n**Example 2**\n\n```text\nInput: numCourses = 2, prerequisites = [[1,0],[0,1]]\nOutput: false\n```\n\n**Example 3**\n\n```text\nInput: numCourses = 4, prerequisites = [[1,0],[2,1],[3,2]]\nOutput: true\n```\n\n## Constraints\n\n- Inputs are sized for local offline execution.\n- Return values follow the method description.",
  "editorial": "Use the graph structure directly: traverse reachable states, maintain visited or distance state, and update the answer when each node or cell is settled.",
  "solution_notes": "```python\nfrom collections import deque\n\nclass Solution:\n    def canFinish(self, numCourses, prerequisites):\n        graph = [[] for _ in range(numCourses)]\n        indeg = [0] * numCourses\n        for course, pre in prerequisites:\n            graph[pre].append(course); indeg[course] += 1\n        queue = deque(i for i, value in enumerate(indeg) if value == 0)\n        done = 0\n        while queue:\n            node = queue.popleft(); done += 1\n            for nxt in graph[node]:\n                indeg[nxt] -= 1\n                if indeg[nxt] == 0: queue.append(nxt)\n        return done == numCourses\n```",
  "hints": [
    "Model the state explicitly.",
    "Prefer linear or near-linear graph traversal when possible."
  ],
